This happens because the alert is within a loop and the condition is checked 3 times.

Here, I slightly modified the code.

Use a `FLAG` in condition block in `for` loop as well as to detect if the word is not found. The advantage of this is that we can stop executing it once we found the match. You can use `break` instead if you want. But since you&#39;re using else condition, a flag is required.

To clarify, the last one is a ternary operator, which check whether the word is found or not. If not, it alerts _wrong word_

