Technically you could use [block string notation](https://graphql.github.io/graphql-spec/June2018/#sec-String-Value) to get around this issue. However, you really should supply dynamic input values using [variables](https://graphql.github.io/graphql-spec/June2018/#sec-Language.Variables) instead of string interpolation. This way you can easily provide any of sort of values (strings, numbers, objects, etc.) and GraphQL will parse them accordingly -- including strings with line breaks.

```
const query = `
  mutation MyMutation ($chapterId: ID!, $content: String!, $title: String!) {
    updateChapter(input: {
      where: {
        id: $chapterId
      },
      data: {
        content: $content
        title: $title
      }
    }) {
      chapter{
        title
        id
        content
      }
    }
  }
`
const variables = {
  chapterId: &#39;...&#39;,
  content: &#39;...&#39;,
  title: &#39;...&#39;,
}
const res = await strapi.request(&quot;post&quot;, &quot;/graphql&quot;, {
  data: {
    query,
    variables,
  },
})
```

Note that `$chapterId` may need to be of the type `String!` instead if that&#39;s what&#39;s called for in the schema. Since variables can also be input object types, instead of providing 3 different variables, you could also provide a single variable to be passed to the `input` argument instead:

```
const query = `
  mutation MyMutation ($input: SomeInputObjectTypeHere!) {
    updateChapter(input: $input) {
      chapter{
        title
        id
        content
      }
    }
  }
`
const variables = {
  input: {
    where: {
      id: &#39;...&#39;,
    },
    data: {
      content: &#39;...&#39;,
      title: &#39;...&#39;,
    },
  },
}
```

Again, just replace `SomeInputObjectTypeHere` with the appropriate type in your schema.

